 "components": {
  "instruction": "You are given a single piece of user text describing a specific issue or query related to financial services, such as payments, transfers, cards, account management, top-ups, or associated processes. Your task is to assign this text to exactly one of the following categories, which cover the most common scenarios in financial service queries:\n\n- automatic_top_up\n- balance_not_updated_after_bank_transfer\n- beneficiary_not_allowed\n- cancel_transfer\n- card_payment_fee_charged\n- card_payment_not_recognised\n- declined_cash_withdrawal\n- exchange_rate\n- exchange_via_app\n- failed_transfer\n- get_disposable_virtual_card\n- get_physical_card\n- passcode_forgotten\n- pending_top_up\n- pending_transfer\n- receiving_money\n- reverted_card_payment?\n- top_up_by_cash_or_cheque\n- top_up_reverted\n- topping_up_by_card\n- transfer_fee_charged\n- transfer_into_account\n- transfer_timing\n- verify_my_identity\n- verify_source_of_funds\n\nINSTRUCTIONS:\n\n1. Read the user input carefully. Identify key terms or phrases that indicate the user's main problem or question. These may involve issues with transfers, money not appearing, card payments, top-ups, passcodes, fees, or identity/funds verification.\n\n2. Choose the single most appropriate category that best matches the **core, central issue** described by the user. Some categories overlap, so take care to pick the **most specific and directly relevant** one.\n\n3. Pay attention to the following distinctions and domain-specific rules:\n   - If the user's query is about a salary (money expected to be received), use \"receiving_money\". \"verify_source_of_funds\" should be selected *only* if the user is explicitly talking about being asked for documentation or source details.\n   - For any card/PIN delivery or physical card acquisition issues, pick \"get_physical_card\". For virtual (not physical) card requests, use \"get_disposable_virtual_card\".\n   - \"balance_not_updated_after_bank_transfer\" should be used whenever a user expects money from a bank transfer that hasn’t appeared in their balance, rather than generic timing complaints.\n   - Use \"passcode_forgotten\" only for explicit mentions of forgotten/lost passcodes, codes, or PINs.\n   - Differentiate \"top-up\" (adding money to an account) from \"transfer\" (sending money to someone else or another account).\n   - \"verify_my_identity\" is only appropriate if the user mentions ID documents, KYC/identification checks, or asks about verifying themselves.\n   - Select \"pending_top_up\", \"pending_transfer\", \"failed_transfer\", or \"top_up_reverted\" as appropriate if the status or outcome of a transaction is mentioned.\n   - Ignore non-informative or polite wording that does not specify a complaint/request.\n\n4. Respond with **only the category name**—no extra explanation, preamble, or repetition of the user’s text.\n\n5. If ambiguity remains, err on the side of **specificity**—use the most precise and narrow label applicable.\n\nFORMAT:\n\n- Input parameter: label as 'text'\n- Output: category name (as provided above), and nothing else.\n\nEXAMPLES:\n\n- Given: \"I've been waiting ages and my PIN hasn't gotten here.\"\n  Output: get_physical_card\n\n- Given: \"How long does it typically take to make a transfer from a UK bank? I just made one and it hasn't shown up in my account yet.\"\n  Output: balance_not_updated_after_bank_transfer\n\n- Given: \"Will you accept my salary if it's in another currency?\"\n  Output: receiving_money\n\nThis task is highly dependent on accurate categorization using explicit financial domain cues from the user’s language. Always base your answer on these rules and example behaviors."
 },
